Given the low volatility environment (0.7% daily) and a ranging trend, a mean reversion strategy is appropriate. This strategy will capitalize on price fluctuations within a defined range, looking for opportunities to buy low and sell high. 

The entry conditions will include two key indicators: the Relative Strength Index (RSI) and a simple moving average (SMA) crossover. The RSI will help identify overbought and oversold conditions, while the SMA crossover will confirm the direction of trades. 

For the exit conditions, we will set both a profit target and a stop loss, allowing for a risk-reward ratio greater than 2.0. Given the ranging trend, a trailing stop can be beneficial, but will be limited to ensure it doesn't cut off profits in a sideways market.

The stop loss will be set at 2% to align with the typical risk per trade, while the take profit will be set at 6%, which meets the target risk-reward ratio. 

Additionally, given the performance requirements, careful calibration of the entry conditions will be essential to ensure we achieve a Sharpe Ratio greater than 1.5 and a win rate above 50%.
